#1 Synchronous colon cancers in the setting of colonic polyposis
Mr. Wedgeworth presents for treatment of his colon cancers.  He has a biopsy-proven cancer in the cecum, and a synchronous growth in the descending colon which is apple-core-type lesion on CT, but biopsy did not confirm malignancy.  I discussed rational for subtotal colectomy with the patient.  He could consider ileorectostomy versus ileostomy versus a J-pouch if this is surgically advisable.  His scans will be sent to Radiology for interpretation.  We will request repeat flexible sigmoidoscopy by the colon and rectal surgeon to assess for rectosigmoid sparing which will hopefully assist with surgical decision-making.  Immunohistochemistry staining has also been requested to rule-out Lynch syndrome.
#2 Skin lesion
I have requested Dermatology evaluation.
#3 Preoperative medical evaluation
Lab work and ECG are requested.  His outside chest x-ray was sent to Radiology for interpretation.  Once these are obtained and satisfactory, patient is OK for anesthesia.  All this was discussed with Dr. Lang, note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

